rs in the high Middle Ages. Bouchard argues that this way of thinking and categorizing-which she terms a "discourse of opposites"-permeated all aspects of medieval thought. She rejects suggestions that it was the result of imprecision, and provides evidence that people of that era sought not to reconcile opposing categories but rather to maintain them. Bouchard scrutinizes the medieval use of opposites in five broad areas: scholasticism, romance, legal disputes, conversion, and the construction of gender. Drawing on research in a series of previously unedited charters and the earliest glossa manuscripts, she demonstrates that this method of constructing reality was a constitutive element of the thought of the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aOpposition, Theory ofxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package 2017z978311062534908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311066587108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017z978311060673740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501716652423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501716652.jpg  a978-3-11-060673-7  Cornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017c2016d2017  a978-3-11-062534-9  COR eBook Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-066587-1  COR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG